defaultThe ability of NHS and social care providers to treat multi-morbidities and the patient as a person rather than focusing on individual conditionsdefault&#xa0;
defaultManaging co-morbidities
default defaultis one of the most significant challenges for a LTC strategy.
default  
default 
defaultArthritis 
defaulthas strong links with other co-morbidities, e.g. cardiovascular and COPD. 
defaultAn Arthritis Care supporter recently described their experience of lack of coordination thus:
default&#xa0;
defaultI am currently under the care of four different consultants at the same hospital &amp; there appears to be great 
defaultdifficultly
defaultdifficulty
default in having appropriate &amp; timely communication between them &amp; myself. If there could be one consultation involving all Specialists, say every 3 months, I would need fewer appointments are get better, faster care. As often one Consultant has to wait for the results or decision made by another Consultant.
default&#xa0;
defaultEvidence 
defaultfrom patient 
defaultorganisations
default such as National Voices shows what people most want is access to 
defaultcare coordinatordefaultsdefault who 
defaultare
default able to arrange packages of care, 
defaultensure that specialist services are joined up, that patients are treated by the right people and in the most appropriate location
default.
default 
defaultThe care coordinator should be tasked with conducting 
default“whole person” needs assessmentsdefault at the beginning of an individual’s care pathway, 
defaultand for 
defaultcollaborative care planning defaultwith patients
default. 
defaultT
defaulthis role may be
default  
default 
defaultdelivered by primary care nurses, 
defaultbut can also be done by trained and well supported volunteers; something Arthritis Care is piloting now.
default Care coordinators should also function as an `internal’ patient advocate, arguing for patients when the system under-performs. 
default&#xa0;
defaultCurrent estimates put the number of LTC patient with care plans at 12%.
default&#xa0;
defaultAnother essential component to dealing with co-morbidities is setting up 
defaultgeneric multidisciplinary teams default(MTDs), which 
defaultaim to move away from single-disease silos of care and to stop patients falling through the gaps as they are shifted from GPs to social workers, outpatients
default, etc
default. Integrated teams do not have to work under the same roof, but they must meet regularly – in person or through teleconferencing – to review at-risk patients and jointly decide care packages. MDTs should comprise GP, nursing and therapy input, as well as case co-ordinators. 
